Severe injuries are usually treated with cream, gauze and bandages, with skin banks using pig and human flesh another aspect of burn treatment, alongside artificial alternatives.But while widely available in developed countries such as the USA, Brazil has no access to artificial materials, and its three functional skills banks barely meet one per cent of the national demand.This forced researchers to come up with an alternative and they turned to the tilapia which is widely farmed in the country, whose skin is usually thrown away.After undergoing a lengthy process of sterilisation, doctors apply the scales directly on to patients burns.The amount of tension, of resistance in tilapia skin is much greater than in human skinDr. Edmar MacielCLICK NEXT TO SEE MORE PICS: WARNING GRAPHIC IMAGES